change for science. Using a database of 34 million articles, their
citations (1945 to 2005), and online availability (1998 to 2005),
I show that as more journal issues came online, the articles referenced
tended to be more recent, fewer journals and articles were cited,
and more of those citations were to fewer journals and articles.
The forced browsing of print archives may have stretched scientists
and scholars to anchor findings deeply into past and present scholarship.
Searching online is more efficient and following hyperlinks quickly
puts researchers in touch with prevailing opinion, but this may accelerate
consensus and narrow the range of findings and ideas built upon.
