la toward south parallel to the Arabian Gulf. The AERONET shortwave Top of Atmosphere Radiative Forcing (TOARF) and at the Bottom of Atmosphere Radiative Forcing (BOARF) have been analyzed and compared with the modeled direct radiative forcing of mineral dust aerosol. The annual modeled TOARF and BOARF are {\&}minus;3.3 and −12 W m{\textless}sup{\textgreater}−2{\textless}/sup{\textgreater}, respectively. However, the annual observed TOARF and BOARF are significantly different at {\&}minus;10 and −52 W m{\textless}sup{\textgreater}−2{\textless}/sup{\textgreater}, respectively. The analysis of observed and modeled TOARF agrees with previous studies in highlighting the need for more accurate specification of surface albedo over the region. Due to the high surface albedo of the central Arabian Peninsula, mineral dust aerosols tend to warm the atmosphere in summer (June–August).{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
