for 1-year average), and with PM10 (1.34; 1.06-1.71 for 1-year average).
Exposure to NO2 was also associated with all-cause mortality (1.17;
1.02-1.34). No association was seen with noncardiopulmonary nonlung
cancer mortality. Conclusions: Living close to major roads and chronic
exposure to NO2 and PM10 may be associated with an increased mortality
due to cardiopulmonary causes. (C) 2006 Lippincott Williams {\&} Wilkins,
Inc.},
